Cell["\<\
Calculation 1 was done at end of class Wednesday 3/25. Calculation 2 at \
beginning of class 3/27.\
\>", "Subsubtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.763304520949601*^9, 3.763304528249754*^9}, {
  3.794305619446727*^9, 3.7943056841769*^9}, {3.7943057791449757`*^9, 
  3.7943057947835007`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"51b593fa-0771-4637-86fe-\
65bdcd3d4318"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The energy density of coal, that is how much heat and light is produced if \
you burn it, is roughly 24 MJ/kg.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Calculation 1: How long could the Sun produce power if it were a \
burning lump of coal?\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\nInputs to calculation:\n\nThe Sun produces energy at the rate of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"3.85", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["10", "26"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["W",
      FontSlant->"Plain"], "."}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "90154a59-af7e-46e4-9c47-677b508bf562"],
 "\n\nThe Sun\[CloseCurlyQuote]s mass is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"1.99", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["10", "30"], "kg"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "605931ee-c48b-4990-a874-412574868de3"],
 ".\n\nPower = Energy / Time\n\nWe got 5,000 years when we did this in class \
with a bit of rounding. It is good practice to repeat the calculation.\n\nIt \
was a great mystery in the late 1800s as to why the Sun \
hadn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t burned out already. The mystery \
wasn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t solved until Einstein discovered that matter itself \
can be a power source. Einstein\[CloseCurlyQuote]s paper saying that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"E", "=", 
    RowBox[{"m", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
     SuperscriptBox["c", "2"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "20256256-8fc1-430e-99a0-2349b21c5f59"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["m", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "51ed88e6-7f93-4366-87fd-050e9a71f3ae"],
 " is the mass of the matter that is turned into energy and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["c", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "020263f5-ff28-4a6c-bffc-dcb1887d27fe"],
 " is the speed of light came out in 1905.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Calculation 2: How many kilograms of coal has to be burned to \
light a 100W bulb on for one year?\n\nCalculation 3: What is 24MJ in kWh\n\n",
  
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Note that a real coal power plant, you don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t actually get \
6.7 kWh of electrical energy for each kg of coal burned, because about 60% of \
the power plant\[CloseCurlyQuote]s power goes out the smokestacks as hot air \
and steam. Only about 40% goes into the power lines as electrical energy.)"
}], "Text",
